# =============================================================================
# Cortex SDK - Test Environment Variables (Template)
# =============================================================================
#
# This is a TEMPLATE file showing available configuration options.
# Copy relevant sections to .env.local and customize for your environment.
#
# =============================================================================

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# LOCAL DEVELOPMENT (Anonymous Local Convex)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Use for rapid iteration without vector search requirements
# Configure these in .env.local:
#
# LOCAL_CONVEX_DEPLOYMENT=anonymous:anonymous-cortex-sdk-local
# LOCAL_CONVEX_URL=http://127.0.0.1:3210

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CLOUD DEVELOPMENT (Managed Convex Deployment)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Use for testing vector search and production-like features
# Configure these in .env.local:
#
# CLOUD_CONVEX_URL=https://your-deployment.convex.cloud
# CLOUD_CONVEX_DEPLOY_KEY=dev:your-deployment|your-key-here

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OPENAI API KEY (Recommended)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Required for embedding generation and LLM-powered features.
# Add to .env.local:
#
# OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AUTOMATIC EMBEDDING GENERATION (Recommended - Enabled by Default)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Enable batteries-included semantic search with automatic embedding generation.
#
# Uses a two-gate approach for safety:
# - Gate 1: OPENAI_API_KEY must be set
# - Gate 2: CORTEX_EMBEDDING must be explicitly set to 'true'
#
# This prevents accidental API costs - you must explicitly opt-in.
#
CORTEX_EMBEDDING=true
#
# With both gates satisfied, the SDK will automatically:
# - Generate embeddings for recall() queries (no manual embedding code!)
# - Generate embeddings for facts during remember()
# - Generate embeddings for vector memories during remember()
# - Enable semantic fact deduplication
#
# Model: text-embedding-3-small (configurable via CortexConfig.embedding.model)
#
# You can also configure embedding explicitly via CortexConfig.embedding for more control.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AUTOMATIC FACT EXTRACTION (Optional)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Enable automatic fact extraction from conversations during remember() calls.
#
# Uses a two-gate approach for safety:
# - Gate 1: An LLM API key must be set (OPENAI_API_KEY or ANTHROPIC_API_KEY)
# - Gate 2: CORTEX_FACT_EXTRACTION must be explicitly set to 'true'
#
# This prevents accidental API costs - you must explicitly opt-in.
#
# CORTEX_FACT_EXTRACTION=true
#
# With both gates satisfied, the SDK will automatically:
# - Extract facts from user/agent conversations
# - Store facts in the Facts Store (Layer 3)
# - Link facts to source conversations
#
# You can also configure LLM explicitly via CortexConfig.llm for more control.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# LLM MODEL CONFIGURATION (Optional)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Configure models for different LLM operations. These act as defaults when
# no model is explicitly specified in API requests.
#
# CORTEX_FACT_EXTRACTION_MODEL
#   Model for extracting facts from conversations.
#   Default: gpt-4o-2024-11-20 (best balance of quality and speed)
#   Recommended alternatives:
#     - gpt-5-mini: Best quality (more entities/relations, 56.9s latency)
#     - gpt-4o-mini: Budget option (lower cost, fewer relations)
#   See Documentation/core-features/fact-extraction.mdx for benchmarks.
#
# CORTEX_FACT_EXTRACTION_MODEL=gpt-4o-2024-11-20
#
# CORTEX_BELIEF_REVISION_MODEL
#   Model for belief revision conflict resolution (ADD, UPDATE, SUPERSEDE decisions).
#   Falls back to CORTEX_FACT_EXTRACTION_MODEL if not set.
#
# CORTEX_BELIEF_REVISION_MODEL=gpt-4o-2024-11-20
#
# CORTEX_CONVERSATION_MODEL
#   Model for conversation responses in CLI templates.
#   Default: gpt-4o-mini (good for interactive responses)
#
# CORTEX_CONVERSATION_MODEL=gpt-4o-mini
#
# Model resolution order (first match wins):
#   1. Explicit model in API request
#   2. Area-specific config field (e.g., factExtractionModel)
#   3. Area-specific env var (e.g., CORTEX_FACT_EXTRACTION_MODEL)
#   4. General config.model field
#   5. Hardcoded default (gpt-4o-2024-11-20 for OpenAI)

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# GRAPH DATABASE CONFIGURATION (Optional)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# For testing graph database integration features
# Configure these in .env.local:
#
# # Neo4j Configuration
# NEO4J_URI=bolt://localhost:7687
# NEO4J_USERNAME=neo4j
# NEO4J_PASSWORD=cortex-dev-password
#
# # Memgraph Configuration
# MEMGRAPH_URI=bolt://localhost:7688
# MEMGRAPH_USERNAME=memgraph
# MEMGRAPH_PASSWORD=cortex-dev-password
#
# Start graph databases with:
#   docker-compose -f docker-compose.graph.yml up -d
#
# See Documentation/07-advanced-topics/05-graph-database-setup.md

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AUTOMATIC GRAPH SYNC (Optional - Enables Knowledge Graph)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Enable automatic graph database sync during remember() and other operations.
#
# Uses a two-gate approach for safety:
# - Gate 1: Connection credentials must be set (NEO4J_URI or MEMGRAPH_URI + auth)
# - Gate 2: CORTEX_GRAPH_SYNC must be explicitly set to 'true'
#
# This prevents accidental graph connections - you must explicitly opt-in.
#
# CORTEX_GRAPH_SYNC=true
#
# With both gates satisfied and using Cortex.create():
# - Automatically connects to the graph database
# - Starts the background sync worker
# - Syncs MemorySpaces, Conversations, Memories, and Facts to the graph
# - Extracts named entities (person, organization, place, product, concept)
# - Creates Entity nodes and typed relationships (e.g., WORKS_AT, LOCATED_IN)
# - Enables graph expansion during recall() for contextual retrieval
#
# Graph Schema Overview:
#   - Memory ←[REFERENCES]→ Conversation
#   - Fact ←[EXTRACTED_FROM]→ Conversation
#   - Fact ←[EXTRACTED_WITH]→ Memory (bidirectional traceability)
#   - Fact ←[MENTIONS]→ Entity
#   - Entity ←[typed relationship]→ Entity (e.g., Sarah --[WORKS_AT]--> Company)
#
# If both NEO4J_URI and MEMGRAPH_URI are set, Neo4j takes priority with a warning.
#
# Example usage:
#   const cortex = await Cortex.create({ convexUrl: process.env.CONVEX_URL! });
#
# You can also configure graph explicitly via CortexConfig.graph for more control.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# RECALL LIMITS CONFIGURATION (Optional)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Configure default limits for recall() operations.
# These can be overridden per-call via the `limits` parameter.
#
# Per-source limits (how many results to fetch from each source):
#
# CORTEX_RECALL_LIMIT_MEMORIES=20
#   Maximum memories to fetch from vector search.
#   Higher values increase context but also latency and cost.
#
# CORTEX_RECALL_LIMIT_FACTS=15
#   Maximum facts to fetch from semantic search.
#   Facts are compact and high-signal, so fewer are often sufficient.
#
# Graph traversal limits (controls exponential relationship expansion):
#
# CORTEX_RECALL_GRAPH_HOPS=2
#   Graph traversal depth. Controls how far to follow relationships.
#   - 0: Disabled (no graph expansion, fastest)
#   - 1: Immediate relationships only
#   - 2: Two-hop traversal (default, good balance)
#   - 3+: Deeper traversal (exponential growth, use with caution)
#
# CORTEX_RECALL_GRAPH_ENTITIES_PER_HOP=5
#   Maximum entities to expand per graph hop.
#   Controls branching factor: 5 entities × 2 hops = up to 25 entities explored.
#
# CORTEX_RECALL_GRAPH_RESULTS_PER_ENTITY=3
#   Maximum memories/facts to fetch per discovered entity.
#   Total graph results ≈ entitiesPerHop × resultsPerEntity × hops.
#
# Final aggregate limit:
#
# CORTEX_RECALL_LIMIT_TOTAL=30
#   Maximum total results returned after merge, dedupe, and ranking.
#   This is the hard cap on items returned to the caller.
#
# Example configurations:
#
# Fast lookups (minimal latency):
#   CORTEX_RECALL_LIMIT_MEMORIES=10
#   CORTEX_RECALL_LIMIT_FACTS=5
#   CORTEX_RECALL_GRAPH_HOPS=0
#   CORTEX_RECALL_LIMIT_TOTAL=15
#
# Deep context (comprehensive retrieval):
#   CORTEX_RECALL_LIMIT_MEMORIES=30
#   CORTEX_RECALL_LIMIT_FACTS=20
#   CORTEX_RECALL_GRAPH_HOPS=2
#   CORTEX_RECALL_GRAPH_ENTITIES_PER_HOP=8
#   CORTEX_RECALL_GRAPH_RESULTS_PER_ENTITY=5
#   CORTEX_RECALL_LIMIT_TOTAL=50

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CONVEX PLAN TIER (Optional)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Specify your Convex subscription plan to automatically configure concurrency
# limits in the resilience layer.
#
# Values:
#   - 'free' or 'starter': Conservative limits (16 concurrent queries/mutations)
#   - 'professional': Higher limits (256 concurrent queries/mutations)
#
# CONVEX_PLAN=free
#
# Based on Convex platform limits:
# @see https://docs.convex.dev/production/state/limits
#
# Free/Starter Plan:
#   - Concurrent queries: 16
#   - Concurrent mutations: 16
#   - Concurrent actions: 64
#
# Professional Plan:
#   - Concurrent queries: 256
#   - Concurrent mutations: 256
#   - Concurrent actions: 256-1000
#
# The SDK uses this to auto-select the appropriate ResiliencePreset:
#   - free/starter → ResiliencePresets.default (maxConcurrent: 16)
#   - professional → ResiliencePresets.batchProcessing (maxConcurrent: 64)
#
# You can also manually select a preset in your code for more control.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# TESTING MODES
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# The test runner automatically detects available configurations:
#
# - If LOCAL_CONVEX_URL is set      → runs local tests
# - If CLOUD_CONVEX_URL is set      → runs managed/cloud tests
# - If both are set                 → runs BOTH test suites
# - Set CONVEX_TEST_MODE explicitly → override auto-detection
#
# Examples:
#   npm run test              → auto-detect and run appropriate suite(s)
#   npm run test:local        → force local tests only
#   npm run test:managed      → force managed/cloud tests only
#   npm run test:both         → run both suites explicitly
#
# For interactive testing:
#   npm run test:interactive        → uses CONVEX_URL from .env.local
#   npm run test:interactive:local  → force local
#   npm run test:interactive:cloud  → force cloud

